commit.message: Release v3.0.1
allow to set user in mutable object

avoid leaking Python handle in timestamp conversion

Adding UTC to a datetime object creates a new Python object.
We therefore need to get rid of the original one.

Fixes #139.
fix version numbers
Release v3.0.0

tools: introduce a socket timeout

Python has blocking connections per default which means that
the download tools can hang indefinitely under some circumstances.
Introduce a default timeout of 60 seconds. It is possible to
change the value via the command line. If the replication runs
into a timeout it stops the download and salvages what was done
so far.
appveyor: switch to Visual Studio 19 and add python 3.8

commit.message: travis: remove boost sources
appveyor: drop python2
travis: switch language to python

switch travis to bionic

Also removes python2 builds and builds for all supported
python 3 versions instead.

update dependencies in README

Remove mention of python2.

remove support for Python2 and Python 3.3

Gets rid of all version-based special cases in the code.
Release v2.15.4
exclude pypy from supported versions

doc: add more information about file updates

Explain how to choose the replication service and
how to run updating in a loop.

reduce required version for boost

We only use the function iterator, which works fine on older
boost versions.
doc: add section about how to use diff files

use a custom HTTP user agent when requesting diffs

Fixes #120.

retry downloading truncated state files

The OSM server may deliver half-written state files in some
rare cases. The result might be a cut or missing timestamp.
Try to detect the situation and download the file again.

Fixes #126.
pyosmium-get-changes: bail out when format is missing for stdout

pyosmium-get-changes: allow to pipe updates to stdout

Use '-o -' together with the new option '--format <something>'.

Fixes #118.
